# SEO Standards — Tom Yam Yadom

Apply every rule below whenever creating or editing any page or product in this project.

---

## 1. Metadata (every page)

Every `page.js` must export a `metadata` object or `generateMetadata` function.
Required fields on every page — all values must be unique to that page:

```js
export const metadata = {
  title: "Page Title | Tom Yam Yadom",
  description: "Under 160 chars. Specific to this page, not recycled from home.",
  alternates: { canonical: "https://www.tomyamyadomherbals.com/page-path" },
};
```

- `description` must be **≤ 160 characters** — check length before saving.
- `alternates.canonical` must be the page's own full URL (with www).
- Never reuse the homepage description on any other page.

---

## 2. Open Graph (every page)

Include `openGraph` in every `metadata` export. Values must be page-specific:

```js
openGraph: {
  title: "Page-specific OG title",
  description: "Page-specific OG description (≤ 160 chars)",
  url: "https://www.tomyamyadomherbals.com/page-path",
  siteName: "Tom Yam Yadom",
  locale: "en_US",
  type: "website", // or "product" for product pages
},
```

Never copy the homepage `openGraph` block onto another page.

---

## 3. Sitemap sync

Whenever a new page or product slug is added, **also update `app/sitemap.js`**:
- Static pages: add a new entry to `staticRoutes`.
- Products: add the slug string to the `PRODUCT_SLUGS` array.

If you know the slug, make the edit automatically without asking.

---

## 4. Structured data — JSON-LD

**Product pages** (`app/products/[slug]/page.js`) must render a `<script type="application/ld+json">` with Product schema:

```js
const jsonLd = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "Product",
  name: product.name,
  description: product.description,
  // image is CONDITIONAL — only include when product.image exists in products.js.
  // Never hardcode a placeholder or non-existent path into JSON-LD.
  ...(product.image ? { image: product.image } : {}),
  brand: { "@type": "Brand", name: "Tom Yam Yadom" },
  category: "Herbal Inhaler",
  offers: {
    "@type": "Offer",
    price: product.price,          // numeric, no currency symbol
    priceCurrency: "USD",
    // PreOrder until Stripe checkout is connected and products are purchasable.
    // Switch to "https://schema.org/InStock" once checkout is live.
    availability: "https://schema.org/PreOrder",
    url: `https://www.tomyamyadomherbals.com/products/${product.slug}`,
    priceValidUntil: /* ISO date string, one year from build date */ "YYYY-MM-DD",
  },
};
// Render as:
// <script type="application/ld+json"
//   dangerouslySetInnerHTML={{ __html: JSON.stringify(jsonLd) }} />
```

> **TODO (keep until done):** Product photos are currently placeholders.
> Once real product photos exist:
> 1. Add an `image` field with the real absolute URL to each product in `app/data/products.js`.
> 2. Verify each product page in [Google's Rich Results Test](https://search.google.com/test/rich-results).
>
> Until then, the schema intentionally omits the `image` field.

**Standard pages** (Home, Story, Shop) should include `Organization` or `WebSite` schema where appropriate.

---

## 5. Images

Always use Next.js `<Image>` — never a bare `<img>` tag.
`alt` text must be descriptive and include relevant keywords:

```jsx
// ❌ BAD
<img src="/inhaler.jpg" />
<Image src="/inhaler.jpg" alt="inhaler" ... />

// ✅ GOOD
<Image
  src="/inhaler.jpg"
  alt="Tom Yam Yadom Thai herbal inhaler — Vitality scent"
  width={600}
  height={600}
/>
```

- `width` and `height` must always be explicit.
- Keywords to include where natural: "Thai herbal inhaler", scent name, "Koh Samui", "aromatherapy".

---

## 6. Heading hierarchy

Each page must have **exactly one `<h1>`**, typically the main page title.
Heading levels must not skip (h1 → h2 → h3, never h1 → h3).

```jsx
// ❌ BAD — two h1s, skipped level
<h1>Shop</h1>
<h1>All Inhalers</h1>
<h3>Vitality</h3>

// ✅ GOOD
<h1>Shop All Thai Herbal Inhalers</h1>
<h2>Scent Collection</h2>
<h3>Vitality</h3>
```
